The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Friday, July 23, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi July 22: The income tax department today extended the last date for filing of returns by salaried and non-corporate assessees by three months to October 31 from July 31, an official release said. Last year also, the government had extended the last date for filing income tax returns by three months to October 31 to facilitate taxpayers. Earlier, the last date for filing income tax returns used to be June 30, which has been fixed at July 31 through amendments in the Income Tax Act.																								 Mumbai, July 22: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) has amended its guidelines on employee stock option and purchase schemes to provide for mandatory disclosures, pricing and appointment of merchant bankers. Subsequent to changes in guidelines in June 2003, the capital market regulator had received queries seeking clarification.																								 Mumbai, July 22: Sebi has asked Rolta India Ltd to discontinue practice of including cost of self-assembled capital equipment in sales and resist from adopting practices inconsistent with the domestic and international accounting standards.																								 New Delhi, July 22: A sharp decline in the performance of the cement and steel sectors during June has pulled down the overall growth rate of the six infrastructure sectors to 3.2 per cent for the month compared with 5.6 per cent in the same month of the previous year. The growth rate of power generation slipped in June.																								 Calcutta, July 22: The Indian Tea Association (ITA) has set up an Indo-Iranian facilitation cell for strengthening tea trade with Iran. 																								 New Delhi, July 22: The government today cleared 28 FDI proposals worth Rs 21 crore mainly in chemicals and petro-chemicals, catering and allied services and software development.																								 Mumbai, July 22: The National Commodities and Derivaties Exchange (NCDEX) will launch eight new commodity futures contracts, including castor seed, sugar and turmeric, beginning tomorrow.
